        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "In some environments you may set form data with null values instead of empty strings. \r\nCurrently the semantic from the BaseInputFilter is, that null is a value and the input is not excluded from the filter if $required == false.\r\n\r\nThis is the relevant snippet from BaseInputFilter::isValid()\r\n{code}\r\n            $input = $this->inputs[$name];\r\n            if (!array_key_exists($name, $this->data) || (is_string($this->data[$name]) && strlen($this->data[$name]) === 0)) {\r\n                if($input instanceof InputInterface) {\r\n                    \/\/ - test if input is required\r\n                    if (!$input->isRequired()) {\r\n                        $this->validInputs[$name] = $input;\r\n                        continue;\r\n                    }\r\n                    \/\/ - test if input allows empty\r\n                    if ($input->allowEmpty()) {\r\n                        $this->validInputs[$name] = $input;\r\n                        continue;\r\n                    }\r\n                }\r\n                \/\/ make sure we have a value (empty) for validation\r\n                $this->data[$name] = '';\r\n            }\r\n{code}\r\nThis is not what I would expect and I'm not sure if this is an issue or not. \r\nBut adding $this->data[$name] === null would be easy and has afaik no side effects.\r\n"
        },
